{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513320"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:08:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:08:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12085"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12085"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.12,0.04,0.05,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4638"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53030"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4638"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-09-12T20:11:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-14T13:21:24+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-10-05T17:44:09+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-23 21:25:46"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12085"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"3779"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38442"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1498"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7059"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42706"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38442"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53030"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old man presents with a three month history of worsening pain along his lower left mandible. The pain is incredibly intense, paroxysmal in nature and lasts for a few seconds to minutes. The pain is triggered by shaving and brushing his teeth, however in between episodes he has no residual abnormal sensation. His medical history is significant for hypertension and he has a 40 pack-year smoking history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 140/85 mmHg, pulse 75/min and SpO2 98% on room air. On light palpation of the lower mandible the patient suddenly winces, pulls away in pain and describes a continuous dull ache lasting for approximately 60 seconds in the area. A cranial nerve examination is performed and is otherwise normal despite hesitancy from the patient not allowing the area to be touched again.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["MRI brain","Neurosurgical referral","Valproate","Phenytoin","Carbamazepine"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has pain due to trigeminal neuralgia. Trigeminal neuralgia usually affects people of middle-age and presents clinically with unilateral neuropathic pain in the distribution of one or more divisions of the trigeminal nerve (cranial nerve 5) with the mandibular and maxillary divisions are most commonly implicated. The pain from trigeminal neuralgia is often described as short in duration, intense and nature and can be triggered by touch. In between episodes however, there are no signs or symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe exact pathophysiology is not known but in some patients vascular compression of the trigeminal ganglion has been implicated. The pain responds to medications used to treat neuropathic pain in about 70% of patients and traditionally the first-line drug used is \u003Cstrong\u003Ecarbamazepine\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E should be performed at the time of presentation to rule out pathology such as multiple sclerosis or cerebellopontine masses. This imaging may show vascular compression of the ganglion and approximately 15-30% of patients may respond to microvascular decompression of the trigeminal ganglion. In this particular case, there is no evidence of any sensory loss or anything to suggest nerve compression. However, the first action should be to give carbamazepine to provide symptomatic relief.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurosurgical referral\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated if MRI brain imaging is suggestive of an intracranial pathology such as the vascular compression of the trigeminal ganglion mentioned above.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhenytoin \u003C/strong\u003Emay be considered for patients who are not responsive to carbamazepine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EValproate \u003C/strong\u003Ecan assist in the management of trigeminal neuralgia, and could be considered in patients refractory to carbamazepine. however there is no evidence to supports its use in managing trigeminal neuralgia. Vaproate can interact with a wide variety of drugs and ideally should be used as monotherapy except in very refractory cases.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Carbamazepine is the first line medical management for trigeminal neuralgia"],"references":["Schug SA, Palmer GM, Scott DA, et al. Acute Pain Management Scientific Evidence 5th edition. 2020. Available from https://www.anzca.edu.au/safety-advocacy/advocacy/college-publications","https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/december/facial-pain-a-diagnostic-challenge","Cruccu, G, Di Stefano G, Truini A. Trigeminal Neuralgia. NEJM 2020; 383:754-63"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38442"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12085"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38442","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38442"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-14T13:21:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-14T13:22:06+09:30","number":7,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2024-09-14T13:21:23+09:30","plagiarismScore":13.6,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4638-7.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T033838Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=bca2437d88bff8de6526750faa57263a1f7c9d4bf4bd4416200cf98d5b213047"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4638"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53030"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degr